CREscendo Tutorial: Analysis of 10X Genomics Adult Mouse Cortex ATAC Chromium v2

Installation

To install the CREscendo package, you can use the code.

devtools::install_github("ChenMengjie/CREscendo")

Then load the following libraries used in this tutorial:

library(Signac)
library(Seurat)
library(EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75)
library(TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene)
library(CREscendo)
library(ggrepel)
library(tictoc)

Dataset: Mouse cortex, ATAC v2, Chromium X

We downloaded the mouse cortex scATAC-seq dataset, which includes peak files and fragment files, from 10x Genomics. The dataset initially contained 8,067 nuclei. We conducted quality control and cell type annotations using Signac as below.

counts <- Read10X_h5("8k_mouse_cortex_ATACv2_nextgem_Chromium_X_filtered_peak_bc_matrix.h5")
metadata <- read.csv(
  file = "8k_mouse_cortex_ATACv2_nextgem_Chromium_X_singlecell.csv",
  header = TRUE,
  row.names = 1
)

brain_assay <- CreateChromatinAssay(
  counts = counts,
  sep = c(":", "-"),
  genome = "mm10",
  fragments = '8k_mouse_cortex_ATACv2_nextgem_Chromium_X_fragments.tsv.gz',
  min.cells = 1
)

brain <- CreateSeuratObject(
  counts = brain_assay,
  assay = 'peaks',
  project = 'ATAC',
  meta.data = metadata
)

# extract gene annotations from EnsDb
annotations <- GetGRangesFromEnsDb(ensdb = EnsDb.Mmusculus.v79)

seqlevels(annotations) <- paste0('chr', seqlevels(annotations))
genome(annotations) <- "mm10"

# add the gene information to the object
Annotation(brain) <- annotations


brain <- NucleosomeSignal(object = brain)

brain$nucleosome_group <- ifelse(brain$nucleosome_signal > 4, 'NS > 4', 'NS < 4')
FragmentHistogram(object = brain, group.by = 'nucleosome_group', region = 'chr1-1-10000000')

brain <- TSSEnrichment(brain, fast = FALSE)


brain$high.tss <- ifelse(brain$TSS.enrichment > 2, 'High', 'Low')
TSSPlot(brain, group.by = 'high.tss') + NoLegend()

brain$pct_reads_in_peaks <- brain$peak_region_fragments / brain$passed_filters * 100
brain$blacklist_ratio <- brain$blacklist_region_fragments / brain$peak_region_fragments

VlnPlot(
  object = brain,
  features = c('pct_reads_in_peaks', 'peak_region_fragments',
               'TSS.enrichment', 'blacklist_ratio', 'nucleosome_signal'),
  pt.size = 0.1,
  ncol = 5
)

brain <- subset(
  x = brain,
  subset = peak_region_fragments > 3000 &
    peak_region_fragments < 100000 &
    pct_reads_in_peaks > 40 &
    blacklist_ratio < 0.025 &
    nucleosome_signal < 4 &
    TSS.enrichment > 2
)
brain



brain <- RunTFIDF(brain)
brain <- FindTopFeatures(brain, min.cutoff = 'q0')
brain <- RunSVD(object = brain)
DepthCor(brain)


brain <- RunUMAP(
  object = brain,
  reduction = 'lsi',
  dims = 2:30
)
brain <- FindNeighbors(
  object = brain,
  reduction = 'lsi',
  dims = 2:30
)
brain <- FindClusters(
  object = brain,
  algorithm = 3,
  resolution = 1.2,
  verbose = FALSE
)

DimPlot(object = brain, label = TRUE) + NoLegend()



# compute gene activities
gene.activities <- GeneActivity(brain)

# add the gene activity matrix to the Seurat object as a new assay
brain[['RNA']] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = gene.activities)
brain <- NormalizeData(
  object = brain,
  assay = 'RNA',
  normalization.method = 'LogNormalize',
  scale.factor = median(brain$nCount_RNA)
)

DefaultAssay(brain) <- 'RNA'
FeaturePlot(
  object = brain,
  features = c('Sst','Pvalb',"Gad2","Neurod6","Rorb","Syt6"),
  pt.size = 0.1,
  max.cutoff = 'q95',
  ncol = 3
)


all.width <- brain@assays$peaks@ranges@ranges@width

allen_rna <- readRDS("allen_brain.rds")
allen_rna <- UpdateSeuratObject(allen_rna)
allen_rna <- FindVariableFeatures(
  object = allen_rna,
  nfeatures = 5000
)

transfer.anchors <- FindTransferAnchors(
  reference = allen_rna,
  query = brain,
  reduction = 'cca',
  dims = 1:30
)

predicted.labels <- TransferData(
  anchorset = transfer.anchors,
  refdata = allen_rna$subclass,
  weight.reduction = brain[['lsi']],
  dims = 2:30
)

brain <- AddMetaData(object = brain, metadata = predicted.labels)
plot1 <- DimPlot(allen_rna, group.by = 'subclass', label = TRUE, repel = TRUE) + NoLegend() + ggtitle('scRNA-seq')
plot2 <- DimPlot(brain, group.by = 'predicted.id', label = TRUE, repel = TRUE) + NoLegend() + ggtitle('scATAC-seq')
plot1 + plot2

#switch back to working with peaks instead of gene activities
DefaultAssay(brain) <- 'peaks'
Idents(brain) <- "predicted.id"

For the annotation of cis-regulatory elements (CREs), we utilized resources from the ENCODE Encyclopedia, specifically the Registry of cCREs Version 3 from SCREEN. This resource details 313,838 candidate CREs in mouse identified by segregating signals across all biospecimen sourced from 169 mouse cell types. These CREs are categorized further into candidate promoters, candidate proximal enhancers, candidate distal enhancers, and are also annotated based on their CTCF binding status.

We have implemented functions to load the CREs from the ENCODE SCREEN V3 directly.

CRE_gr <- CREscendo:::load_CRE_annotations(genome = "mm10")

Creating a CREscendo Test Data Object

In the CREscendo test, Tn5 cleavage frequencies are used as the input. However, this information is not readily available in the peak file alone. To obtain Tn5 cleavage data, we need to screen the fragment files. Given that these fragment files are typically quite large, we opt for the Tabix-indexed file format. Tabix files are compressed and indexed, allowing for efficient data retrieval.

The PrepareCREscendoObject function serves as our tool for constructing a CREscendo object. This involves several steps:

  1. Processing and annotating Genomic Peaks: Initially, we process genomic peaks, which are typically stored in a GenomicRanges object (peaks_gr).

  2. Associating Peaks with CREs: We associate these peaks with cis-regulatory elements (CREs), thereby establishing their regulatory context.

  3. Compiling Cleavage Site Counts: The core aspect of the process involves compiling counts of cleavage sites. This requires accessing the Tabix-indexed file (tabix_file) containing relevant fragment data.

The PrepareCREscendoObject function expects the following inputs:

  • peaks_gr: GenomicRanges object containing genomic peak locations.
  • tabix_file: Path to a Tabix-indexed file containing fragments relevant to the peaks.
  • cell_annotation: Data frame containing cell annotations with columns for cell name and cell type.
  • celltype_list (Optional): A vector of cell types to include in the analysis. If NULL, all unique cell types from cell_annotation will be used.
  • CRE_gr: GenomicRanges object for cis-regulatory elements.
  • tssRegion: Numeric vector of length 2 specifying the region around transcription start sites to consider for annotation (defaults to c(-1000, 1000)).
  • TxDb: A TxDb object containing transcript annotations.
  • annoDb: Character string, the Bioconductor annotation package for organism-specific data. Default is org.Hs.eg.db for human.
  • multiCREs: Logical value indicating whether to include peaks with multiple CREs (TRUE) or all peaks (FALSE). Default is TRUE.

This function streamlines the process, allowing for efficient preparation and construction of the necessary data object for the CREscendo test.

We applied PrepareCREscendoObject to extract Tn5 cleavage sites for selected cell types this dataset.

cells <- colnames(x = brain@assays$peaks)
cell_type_list <- c("L2/3 IT", "Oligo", "L4", "Astro")
cell_annotation <- data.frame(celltype = brain@active.ident[brain@active.ident%in%cell_type_list],
                              cellname = cells[brain@active.ident%in%cell_type_list])

library(TxDb.Mmusculus.UCSC.mm10.knownGene)
mouse_CREscendo  <- PrepareCREscendoObject(peaks.gr, tabix.file, cell_annotation, cell_type_list,
                                         CRE_gr, tssRegion=c(-1000, 1000), TxDb=TxDb.Mmusculus.UCSC.mm10.knownGene, annoDb =  "org.Mm.eg.db")

Tn5 cleavage sites are identified by using the start and end sites of each segment from fragment files. We annotate each peak using ENCODE-defined CREs. For peaks with k overlapping CREs, we divide the peak into k+1 segments (cre1, cre2, , crek) plus an additional segment for base pairs within the peak not covered by any CREs. For each cell type, we construct a frequency vector that represents the number of cleavage sites falling within each segment. The final CREscendo object contains annotated peaks, CRE associations, and cleavage event counts for further analysis.

Testing CRE Association with specified cell types within a CREscendo Object

The main function CREtest() performs chi-squared tests on CREs associated with peaks within a CREscendo object. It evaluates differential CRE activities between two groups of cells.

The required input includes: - x: A CREscendo object containing the necessary datasets for CRE analysis. - celltypes: One or two cell types. Must be cell types included in the CREscendo object. If one cell type is specified, the comparison will be made between the specified cell type and all other cell types. If two cell types are specified, the comparison will be made between the two specified cell types.

For each peak, we perform a chi-square test with degrees of freedom equal to k (k is the number of overlapping CREs). In the chi-square tests for comparison, with two cell types A and B, we conduct the test first using A as the reference population, and then repeat using B. The final p-value is determined as the maximum (less significant) from these two tests. After generating test statistics for all peaks, we apply false discovery rate (FDR) adjustments to correct for multiple comparisons. We further quantified the contribution of CRE by breaking down the overall chi-square statistic into partial chi-square statistic from each CRE.

As an example, we performed the CREscendo test between L2/3 IT cells and Oligodendrocytes in mouse cortex dataset.

tic()
mouse_comparison1 <- CREtest(mouse_CREscendo, celltypes = c("L2/3 IT", "Oligo"))
toc()

To refine our results from the chi-squared test, we can utilize the Filter() function. This function is designed to extract and return high-confidence results from the summary component of the chi-squared test, enabling prioritized downstream analysis. The Filter() function accepts the following parameters:

  • x: A CREscendoTested object containing the results from CRE association tests.
  • fdr_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the false discovery rate (FDR) adjusted p-value threshold for filtering the results. The default is 0.05.
  • coverage_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the cutoff of the number of fragments across all cells within the same type for each peak region for filtering the results. The default is 100.
  • abs_diff_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the cutoff of the absolute difference in the CRE frequencies between two cell types. The default is 0.2. By applying these filtering criteria, we can focus our analysis on the most significant relevant CRE associations.
mouse_comparison1_summary <- Filter(mouse_comparison1)

Visualization of CREscendo Test Results

The function Visualize() is designed to visualize cleavage sites of different cell types for a specific peak or peaks from a specific gene within a CREscendoTested object. This function facilitates the extraction and visualization of relevant data, including cleavage sites, CRE annotations, and CRE frequencies within tested cell types.

The following is a visualization of the CREscendo test results for a specific peak (chr7-139615710-139616653).

Visualize(mouse_comparison1, which_peak = "chr7-139615710-139616653")

If you are interested in a specific peak, like the contribution of each CRE to the chi-square statistics, you can extract more details using the Extract() function.

Comparing with differential accessbility analysis

For the PBMC_multiome dataset, we performed differential accessibility (DA) tests between different cell types. We select logistic regression for the test and include the total number of peaks as a covariate to compensate for variations in sequencing depth as recommended in Signac.

DefaultAssay(brain) <- 'peaks'
tic()
da_peaks <- FindMarkers(
  object = brain,
  ident.1 = c("L2/3 IT"),
  ident.2 = c("Oligo"),
  test.use = 'LR',
  latent.vars = 'nCount_peaks'
)
toc()
## 1865.558 sec elapsed

We further compared the results from CREscendo and DA tests.

chisq_test_summary <- Summarize(mouse_comparison1)
commons <- intersect(rownames(chisq_test_summary), rownames(da_peaks))
all_stats <- cbind(chisq_test_summary[commons, ], da_peaks[commons, ])


# Updated ggplot2 code with ggrepel for non-overlapping text labels
dq <- ggplot(all_stats, aes(x = avg_log2FC, y = chisq_stat)) +
  geom_point( size = 0.8) +
  geom_text_repel(data = subset(all_stats, chisq_stat > 2000),
                  aes(label = SYMBOL),
                  max.overlaps = Inf,
                  box.padding = 0.5,
                  point.padding = 0.5,
                  size = 3,  color = 'darkred') +
  xlim(-6, 6) +  # Slightly wider x-axis limits
  ylim(min(all_stats$chisq_stat), max(all_stats$chisq_stat) + 500) +  # Extend y-axis if necessary
  theme_classic() + labs(title = "L2/3 IT vs. Oligo", x = "Avg log2FC", y = "Chi-square statistics") +
  theme(plot.margin = margin(1, 1, 1, 1, "cm"))  # Set x-axis limits
